## How Judging Works — Read This

Judging is **two-phase**. Every team is AI-screened first. Top 8 advance to human judges.

### Phase 2 — AI Screening (Claude, 6 passes)

| Pass | What Claude looks for |
|---|---|
| 1 — Repo Archaeology | Tech stack, template detection, **commit history metadata**, README summary, key files |
| 2 — Code Deep Dive | Clever solutions, novel API use, architectural decisions. Does NOT penalize messy code or missing tests. |
| 3 — Innovation Audit | Checks against 13 common archetypes (LangChain+Pinecone CRUD, basic todo apps, boilerplate chatbots). Scores "senior engineer surprise factor." |
| 4 — Visual/UX Review | Reviews **up to 5 screenshots**. No screenshots = UX score of 0. |
| 5 — Pool Comparison | Ranks us against all other submissions |
| 6 — Synthesis | Opus + 8k thinking budget. 9–10 = exceptional. Missing UI or no demo = 1–4. |

### What this means for the build

- **Write a real README** — Pass 1 reads it. Explain what Halo is, the problem, the stack, how to run it.
- **Commit throughout the sprint** — commit history is analyzed. One dump commit at the end looks like a template clone.
- **Upload 5 screenshots before deadline** — if we skip this, UX = 0 on Pass 4.
- **Do not let Halo look like a todo app** — the Innovation Audit (Pass 3) checks for exactly this. The drift detection framing must be clear from the repo and README.
- **Deploy and submit the demo URL** — Demo & Communication is 5% and requires a working URL.
- **The Synthesis pass uses Opus with extended thinking** — shallow implementations won't survive it. The architecture needs to be real.

### Phase 3 — Final Round (Top 8 only, human judges)
Technical Execution rises to **25%** (from 20% in AI screening). If we make top 8, the engineering quality is what wins.

